            <fr:title text="TPE Processes Intro">TPE Processes Intro</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p><fr:link href="/007U/" title="Deliberate-Practice" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/007U/" display-uri="007U" type="local">Deliberate-Practice</fr:link> (1/66)</html:p>
            <html:p>The process abstraction, what the OS has to support to maintain it, and the data structure that holds it together.</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>5</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>12</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/FCHM/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>FCHM</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/FCHM/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Process">Process</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><html:p>A running program, plus all the state the OS needs to pause it and resume it later. A process consists of:</html:p><html:ol><html:li><html:strong>Memory</html:strong>: an <fr:link href="/7MH4/" title="Address space" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/7MH4/" display-uri="7MH4" type="local">Address space</fr:link> holding the program's code, stack, and heap.</html:li>
  <html:li><html:strong>Registers</html:strong>: general-purpose registers carrying current computation, plus special-purpose registers:</html:li>
  <html:ul><html:li><html:strong>Program counter (PC)</html:strong>: the next instruction to run.</html:li>
    <html:li><html:strong>Stack pointer and frame pointer</html:strong>: where the process sits on its stack.</html:li></html:ul></html:ol><html:p>A process moves between three <html:strong>states</html:strong>:</html:p><html:ul><html:li><html:em>running</html:em>: currently on a CPU.</html:li>
  <html:li><html:em>ready</html:em>: runnable, waiting for the <fr:link href="/B8GC/" title="Scheduling" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/B8GC/" display-uri="B8GC" type="local">Scheduling</fr:link> to give it a CPU.</html:li>
  <html:li><html:em>blocked</html:em>: waiting on I/O or another event, not runnable.</html:li></html:ul>
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2026</fr:year><fr:month>5</fr:month><fr:day>12</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Remark</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>Threads (see <fr:link href="/16TG/" title="Concurrency Intro" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/16TG/" display-uri="16TG" type="local">Concurrency Intro</fr:link>) share an address space within a process but each have their own PC, register set, and stack.</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
</fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>5</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>12</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/JJ45/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>JJ45</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/JJ45/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Process API">Process API</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><html:p>The minimum operations any OS must expose for working with <fr:link href="/FCHM/" title="Process" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/FCHM/" display-uri="FCHM" type="local">Process</fr:link>es:</html:p><html:ol><html:li><html:strong>Create</html:strong>: load a program from disk, set up its address space (stack, heap, code), and jump to <html:code>main</html:code>. The OS also initializes <html:code>argc</html:code>/<html:code>argv</html:code>.</html:li>
  <html:li><html:strong>Destroy</html:strong>: kill a misbehaving or unwanted process.</html:li>
  <html:li><html:strong>Wait</html:strong>: block until another process completes — useful for ordering dependent work.</html:li>
  <html:li><html:strong>Miscellaneous control</html:strong>: e.g. suspend / resume.</html:li>
  <html:li><html:strong>Status</html:strong>: report on running processes.</html:li></html:ol>
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2026</fr:year><fr:month>5</fr:month><fr:day>12</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Remark</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>The stack is allocated up front. The heap starts small and grows via <html:code>malloc</html:code>, which calls into the OS (<html:code>brk</html:code>/<html:code>sbrk</html:code>) when it runs out of headroom.</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
<html:p>On Unix, the concrete realization of this API uses <html:code>fork()</html:code>, <html:code>wait()</html:code>, and <html:code>exec()</html:code> — covered separately.</html:p></fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors />
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>5</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>12</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/JE53/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>JE53</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/JE53/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Process control block">Process control block</fr:title>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><html:p>The kernel-side data structure holding all per-process state. There is one PCB per <fr:link href="/FCHM/" title="Process" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/FCHM/" display-uri="FCHM" type="local">Process</fr:link>, threaded together into the <html:em>process list</html:em>. The PCB is what the OS reads and writes during a <fr:link href="/OKCI/" title="Context switch" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/OKCI/" display-uri="OKCI" type="local">Context switch</fr:link>: the saved register set lives here, as does the process state, the open files, the parent pointer, and so on.</html:p><html:p>An example from <html:code>xv6</html:code>:</html:p><html:pre><![CDATA[// the registers xv6 will save and restore
// to stop and subsequently restart a process
struct context {
  int eip;
  int esp;
  int ebx;
  int ecx;
  int edx;
  int esi;
  int edi;
  int ebp;
};
// the different states a process can be in
enum proc_state { UNUSED, EMBRYO, SLEEPING, RUNNABLE, RUNNING, ZOMBIE };
// the information xv6 tracks about each process
// including its register context and state
struct proc {
  char *mem;                 // Start of process memory
  uint sz;                   // Size of process memory
  char *kstack;              // Bottom of kernel stack for this process
  enum proc_state state;     // Process state
  int pid;                   // Process ID
  struct proc *parent;       // Parent process
  void *chan;                // If non-zero, sleeping on chan
  int killed;                // If non-zero, have been killed
  struct file *ofile[NOFILE]; // Open files
  struct inode *cwd;         // Current directory
  struct context context;    // Switch here to run process
  struct trapframe *tf;      // Trap frame for the current interrupt
};]]></html:pre>
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2026</fr:year><fr:month>5</fr:month><fr:day>12</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Remark</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:link href="/63U3/" title="Thread" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/63U3/" display-uri="63U3" type="local">Thread</fr:link>s need an analogous <html:em>thread control block</html:em>; see <fr:link href="/16TG/" title="Concurrency Intro" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/16TG/" display-uri="16TG" type="local">Concurrency Intro</fr:link>.</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
</fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
